Let's say you have a loop inside a function. Break would exit the loop, and continue with the rest of the function. Return would exit the function entirely.

For example, here is a function that takes a c-style array and returns the sum of its contents. We have decided we want to break the program by stopping at the third element.
int array_sum(int *p_arr, int size)
{
 int acc = 0;
 for (int i = 0; i < size; i++)
 {
  acc += *(p_arr + i);
  if (i == 3) { break; } // Option A
  if (i == 3) { return acc; } // Option B
 }
 printf("Finished summing array.);
 return acc;
}
In Option A, the string would still be printed.
In Option B, the value would be returned and the function exited right away, so the printf after the loop ends is not executed

